Wayward husband
comes to his senses...

1623
01:51:51,534 --> 01:51:53,695
returns to his wife...

1624
01:51:53,770 --> 01:51:56,739
with whom he's established
a long and sustaining love.

1625
01:51:58,074 --> 01:52:01,976
Heartless young woman left alone
in her arctic desolation.

1626
01:52:05,148 --> 01:52:07,139
Music up with a swell.

1627
01:52:10,186 --> 01:52:11,915
Final commercial.

1628
01:52:14,724 --> 01:52:18,216
And here are a few scenes
from next week's show.

1629
01:52:30,337 --> 01:52:32,271
How'd it go?

1630
01:52:48,755 --> 01:52:53,454
Mr. Jensen was unhappy at the idea
of taking Howard Beale off the air.

1631
01:52:54,761 --> 01:52:56,956
Mr. Jensen thinks Howard Beale
is bringing...

1632
01:52:57,030 --> 01:53:00,830
a very important message
to the American people.

1633
01:53:03,136 --> 01:53:06,503
So he wants Howard Beale on the air,
and he wants him kept on.

1634
01:53:08,675 --> 01:53:11,940
Mr. Jensen feels we're too catastrophic
in our thinking.

1635
01:53:12,012 --> 01:53:14,503
l argued that television
was a volatile industry...

1636
01:53:14,581 --> 01:53:18,415
in which success and failure
were determined week by week.

1637
01:53:19,453 --> 01:53:22,354
Mr. Jensen said he did not like
volatile industries...

1638
01:53:22,422 --> 01:53:26,153
and suggested with a certain
sinister silkiness...

1639
01:53:27,627 --> 01:53:31,222
that volatility in business
usually reflected bad management.

1640
01:53:32,532 --> 01:53:35,501
He didn't really care if Howard Beale
was the number one show or the 50th.

1641
01:53:35,569 --> 01:53:38,060
He didn't really care
if the Beale show lost money.

1642
01:53:39,206 --> 01:53:41,800
He wants Howard Beale on the air...

1643
01:53:41,875 --> 01:53:44,105
and he wants him kept on.

1644
01:53:44,177 --> 01:53:48,307
l would describe his position on this
as inflexible.

1645
01:53:50,217 --> 01:53:52,185
Where does that put us, Diana?

1646
01:53:53,286 --> 01:53:56,847
That puts us in the shithouse.
That's where that puts us.

1647
01:53:59,626 --> 01:54:02,527
Do you want me to go through this?

1648
01:54:03,630 --> 01:54:07,430
The Beale show Q score
is down to 33.

1649
01:54:08,535 --> 01:54:12,062
Most of this loss occurred in the child
and teen and 18-34 categories...

1650
01:54:12,139 --> 01:54:14,972
which were our key core markets.

1651
01:54:16,143 --> 01:54:18,805
lt's the AR department's carefully
considered judgment, and mine...

1652
01:54:18,879 --> 01:54:23,509
that if we get rid of Beale, we should
maintain a respectable share...

1653
01:54:23,583 --> 01:54:25,778
with a comparable Q level.

1654
01:54:25,852 --> 01:54:29,344
The other show segments, Sybil the
Soothsayer, Jim Webbing, Vox Populi...

1655
01:54:29,423 --> 01:54:32,483
have all developed
their own audiences.

1656
01:54:32,559 --> 01:54:37,121
Our AR reports show that it is Beale
that is the destructive force here.

1657
01:54:38,331 --> 01:54:40,697
Minimally, we're talking about...

1658
01:54:40,767 --> 01:54:43,759
a ten-point differential in shares.

1659
01:54:43,837 --> 01:54:45,805
l think Joe oughta spell it out
for us.

1660
01:54:47,808 --> 01:54:50,902
A 28 share
is 80,000 dollar minutes.

1661
01:54:50,977 --> 01:54:53,673
l think we can sell complete positions
on the whole.

1662
01:54:53,747 --> 01:54:56,443
As a matter of fact, we're just getting
into the pre-Christmas gift-sellers...

1663
01:54:56,516 --> 01:55:00,111
and the agencies are coming back to me
with four-dollar CPMs.

1664
01:55:00,187 --> 01:55:05,215
lf that's any indication, we're talking
$40-$45 million loss in annual revenues.

1665
01:55:05,292 --> 01:55:08,523
- Want the flak from the affiliates?
- We know all about it, Herb.

1666
01:55:08,595 --> 01:55:12,326
You would describe Mr. Jensen's position
on Beale as inflexible?

1667
01:55:12,399 --> 01:55:15,300
lntractable and adamantine.

1668
01:55:17,170 --> 01:55:20,367
What do we do about this Beale
son of a bitch?

1669
01:55:22,542 --> 01:55:24,806
l suppose we'll have to kill him.

1670
01:55:27,681 --> 01:55:30,650
l don't suppose you have any ideas
on that, Diana?

1671
01:55:34,121 --> 01:55:35,554
Well...

1672
01:55:37,424 --> 01:55:40,120
what would you fellas say
to an assassination?

1673
01:55:42,028 --> 01:55:44,588
l think l can get
the Mao Tse-tung people...

1674
01:55:44,664 --> 01:55:47,258
to kill Beale for us
as one of their shows.

1675
01:55:48,368 --> 01:55:53,032
ln fact, it'll make a hell of
a kick-off show for the season.

1676
01:55:53,106 --> 01:55:56,041
We're facing heavy opposition on the
other networks for Wednesday nights...

1677
01:55:56,109 --> 01:55:59,567
and the " Mao Tse-tung Hour"
could use a sensational opener.

1678
01:56:01,815 --> 01:56:05,444
lt could be done right on camera
in the studio.

1679
01:56:07,087 --> 01:56:09,317
We oughta get a fantastic
look-in audience...

1680
01:56:09,389 --> 01:56:12,517
for the assassination of Howard Beale
as our opening show.

1681
01:56:13,593 --> 01:56:16,289
lf Beale dies...

1682
01:56:16,363 --> 01:56:20,459
what would our continuing obligation
to the Beale Corporation be?

1683
01:56:20,534 --> 01:56:23,594
l know our contract with Beale
contains a buy-out clause...

1684
01:56:23,670 --> 01:56:25,865
triggered by his death
or incapacity.

1685
01:56:25,939 --> 01:56:29,375
There must be a formula for
the computation of the purchase price.

1686
01:56:29,442 --> 01:56:33,435
Offhand, l think it was based on
a multiple of 1975 earnings...

1687
01:56:33,513 --> 01:56:37,313
with a base period in 1975,
which l think was 50 percent...

1688
01:56:37,384 --> 01:56:40,217
of salary, plus 25 percent
of the first year's profit...

1689
01:56:40,287 --> 01:56:43,415
multiplied by the unexpired portion
of the contract.

1690
01:56:43,490 --> 01:56:45,390
l don't think the show...

1691
01:56:45,458 --> 01:56:48,018
has any substantial syndication value,
would you say, Diana?

1692
01:56:48,094 --> 01:56:50,062
Syndication profits are minimal.

1693
01:56:51,231 --> 01:56:54,029
We're talking about a capital crime.

1694
01:56:55,068 --> 01:56:57,832
The network can't be implicated.

1695
01:57:08,215 --> 01:57:12,413
l hope you don't have any hidden
tape machines in this office, Frank.

1696
01:57:14,521 --> 01:57:17,513
The issue is,
shall we kill Howard Beale or not?

1697
01:57:17,591 --> 01:57:20,185
l'd like to hear
some more opinions on that.

1698
01:57:20,260 --> 01:57:23,718
l don't see we have any option.
Let's kill the son of a bitch.

1699
01:57:23,797 --> 01:57:25,458
Ladies and gentlemen,
let's hear it!

1700
01:57:25,532 --> 01:57:27,261
How do you feel?

1701
01:57:27,334 --> 01:57:28,995
We're mad as hell...

1702
01:57:29,069 --> 01:57:31,799
and we're not gonna
take this anymore!

1703
01:57:31,871 --> 01:57:35,637
Ladies and gentlemen, the " Network
News Hour" with Sybil the Soothsayer...

1704
01:57:39,212 --> 01:57:43,546
Jim Webbing and his
lt's-the-Emmes-Truth Department.

1705
01:57:45,919 --> 01:57:49,980
Miss Mata Hari
and her skeletons in the closet.

1706
01:57:52,425 --> 01:57:54,689
Tonight another segment
of " Vox Populi."

1707
01:57:59,499 --> 01:58:03,868
And starring the Mad Prophet
of the Airways, Howard Beale!

1708
01:58:23,423 --> 01:58:27,860
...network news anchorman
on the UBS " Network News Show" ...

1709
01:58:27,927 --> 01:58:31,886
known to millions
as the Mad Profit of the Airwaves...

1710
01:58:31,965 --> 01:58:35,731
was shot to death tonight in
a fusillade of automatic rifle fire...

1711
01:58:35,802 --> 01:58:38,032
just as he began
this evening's broadcast.

1712
01:58:38,104 --> 01:58:41,562
We never compromise,
so why should you?

1713
01:58:41,641 --> 01:58:45,042
Canada Dry Mixers.
Why compromise?

1714
01:58:45,111 --> 01:58:48,740
Have you seen the other side
of where you live?

1715
01:58:48,815 --> 01:58:52,649
- What's this stuff?
- Some cereal. lt's good for you.

1716
01:58:52,719 --> 01:58:55,620
- Did you try it?
- l'm not gonna try it. You try it.

1717
01:58:55,689 --> 01:58:58,157
l'm not gonna try it.

1718
01:58:58,224 --> 01:59:00,215
- Let's get Mikey to try it!
- Yeah!

1719
01:59:00,293 --> 01:59:02,261
He won't eat it.
He hates everything.

1720
01:59:02,329 --> 01:59:06,288
The extraordinary incident occurred in
full view of his millions of viewers.

1721
01:59:06,366 --> 01:59:10,803
The assassins were members of
the Ecumenical Liberation Army...

1722
01:59:10,870 --> 01:59:12,997
two of whom were apprehended.

1723
01:59:13,073 --> 01:59:16,941
The leader of the group known
as the Great Ahmed Khan escaped.

1724
01:59:17,010 --> 01:59:19,478
This was the story of Howard Beale...

1725
01:59:19,546 --> 01:59:23,812
the first known instance of a man who
was killed because he had lousy ratings.

